The reaction in favour of the historian began at the commencement of the present century. Spalding’s careful study of the text of Quintilian led him to declare emphatically against the theory which attributed the authorship of the Dialogue to the great rhetorician¹ ; and the way was thus cleared for a return to Tacitus. It was under Spalding's auspices also² that the first intimation was made of the discovery of a parallelism which seemed at once to decide the question in the historian's favour, 3ηά which has therefore playeda large part in all subsequent discussions.
